OUTPUT FOLDER GUIDE — Fintech Text Analysis Project

This folder contains all intermediate and final results.  
Below is an explanation of each file.

------------------------------------------------------------
1. corpus.csv
- Raw extracted text from all PDFs.
- Columns: bank, year, filename, raw_text.
- Purpose: archive of text extraction step.
- Not usually needed for analysis.

2. corpus_clean.csv
- Cleaned version of corpus.csv.
- Columns: bank, year, filename, word_count, clean_text.
- Purpose: normalized text used for keyword search.
- Not usually needed unless debugging text cleaning.

------------------------------------------------------------
3. keyword_freq_long.csv
- Long-format keyword frequencies.
- Columns: bank, year, group (FTII/FTOI), keyword, count, rel_freq.
- Purpose: shows how often each keyword appears per bank-year.
- Useful for detailed inspection.

4. keyword_freq_wide.csv
- Wide-format keyword frequencies.
- Columns: bank, year, FTII__keyword, FTOI__keyword (relative frequencies).
- Purpose: machine-friendly table for later normalization.

5. keyword_freq_normalized.csv
- Min–max normalized keyword frequencies.
- Columns: same as keyword_freq_long, plus norm_freq.
- Purpose: puts all keywords on [0,1] scale before weighting.

------------------------------------------------------------
6. entropy_weights.csv
- Entropy weights per keyword.
- Columns: group, keyword, entropy, weight_raw, weight_norm.
- Purpose: shows how much weight each keyword contributes to indices.

------------------------------------------------------------
7. fintech_indices_long.csv
- Long-format fintech indices.
- Columns: bank, year, group (FTII/FTOI), index_value.
- Purpose: tidy format for plotting trends by group.

8. fintech_indices_wide.csv
- Wide-format fintech indices.
- Columns: bank, year, FTII, FTOI, FTI.
- Purpose: main output of text-mining.
- This is the file you use for analysis.

------------------------------------------------------------
9. bank_financials.csv
- Manually provided financial data.
- Columns: bank, year, ROA, ROE, Assets, CAR, and other controls.
- Purpose: external ground-truth data for regression.
- Must be updated whenever new PDFs are added.

10. analysis_dataset.csv
- Merged dataset (indices + financials).
- Columns: bank, year, FTII, FTOI, FTI, ROA, ROE, Assets, CAR, etc.
- Purpose: final dataset for regression.
- This is the most important input for econometric analysis.

------------------------------------------------------------
11. regression_pooled_ols.txt
- Regression results using pooled OLS.
- Contains coefficients, standard errors, t-stats, p-values.
- Purpose: baseline regression ignoring bank effects.

12. regression_fixed_effects.txt
- Regression results using Fixed Effects (if model runs).
- Controls for bank-specific factors.
- Purpose: within-bank variation analysis.

13. regression_random_effects.txt
- Regression results using Random Effects.
- Purpose: efficient model if RE assumptions hold.

14. regression_pcse.txt
- Regression results using robust OLS (PCSE style).
- Purpose: accounts for heteroskedasticity and correlation.

------------------------------------------------------------
15. desc_stats.csv
- Descriptive statistics for variables.
- Mean, std, min, max, quartiles.
- Purpose: overview of dataset distribution.

16. corr_matrix.csv
- Correlation matrix for variables.
- Purpose: check relationships and collinearity.

17. vif.csv
- Variance Inflation Factor for regressors.
- Purpose: detect multicollinearity.
- Only generated if dataset has enough rows.

------------------------------------------------------------
SUMMARY — WHICH FILES MATTER MOST

For interpretation and reporting:
- fintech_indices_wide.csv  (indices per bank-year)
- analysis_dataset.csv      (merged dataset: indices + financials)
- regression_*.txt          (regression results)
- desc_stats.csv, corr_matrix.csv (diagnostics)

The other files (corpus, keyword frequencies, entropy weights) are
intermediate and mainly useful for debugging or auditing the process.

END OF FILE
